\u00e9e \u00e0 l'Inde bouddhique |language=fr |trans-title=Around B\u0101miy\u0101n: From Hellenized Bactria to Buddhist India |publisher=De Boccard |editor-first=G. |editor-last=Duc\u0153ur |chapter=Mat\u00e9riaux pour une histoire de la l\u00e9gende et du culte de Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa: une relecture d\u2019un fragment inscrit retrouv\u00e9 \u00e0 Silao (Bih\u0101r) |trans-chapter=Materials for a History of the Legend and Cult of Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa: A Rereading of an Inscribed Fragment Found at Silao (Bih\u0101r) |url=https://eprints.soas.ac.uk/17114/1/Tournier%20Kasyapa%20Silao%202012.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190619171841/https://eprints.soas.ac.uk/17114/1/Tournier%20Kasyapa%20Silao%202012.pdf |archive-date=19 June 2019 |url-status=live |oclc=823280495}}\n* {{Citation |last1=Tournier |first1=V. |title=Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa, His Lineage, and the Wish for Buddhahood: Reading Anew the Bodhgay\u0101 Inscriptions of Mah\u0101n\u0101man |journal=[[Indo-Iranian Journal]] |date=2014 |volume=57 |issue=1\u20132 |pages=1\u201360 |doi=10.1163/15728536-05701001|url=https://eprints.soas.ac.uk/18263/1/Tournier%20Mahanaman%20IIJ%202014.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170921230648/http://eprints.soas.ac.uk/18263/1/Tournier%20Mahanaman%20IIJ%202014.pdf |archive-date=21 September 2017 |url-status=live}}\n* {{Citation |last=Tsukamoto |first=K. |year=1963 |title=Mah\u0101ka\u015byapa's Precedence to \u0100nanda in the R\u0101jag\u1e5bha Council |journal=Indogaku Bukkyogaku Kenkyu [Journal of Indian and Buddhist Studies] |volume=11 |issue=2 |url=https://www.jstage.jst.go.jp/article/ibk1952/11/2/11_2_824/_pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180921034502/https://www.jstage.jst.go.jp/article/ibk1952/11/2/11_2_824/_pdf |pages=824{{en dash}}817 |archive-date=21 September 2018 |url-status=live|doi=10.4259/ibk.11.824 }}<!--some Japanese journals number their pages in reverse order-->\n* {{Citation |last1=Voros |first1=Sebastjan |title=Mahakashyapa's Smile: Language, Silence, and Mysticism |journal=Synthesis Philosophica |date=January 2014 |volume=58 |issue=2 |pages=387\u2013402 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/292087649 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217191449/https://www.researchgate.net/publication/292087649_Mahakashyapa's_Smile_Language_Silence_and_Mysticism |archive-date=17 February 2020 |url-status=live}}\n* {{Citation |last=Welter |first=A. |year=2000 |chapter=Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa\u2019s Smile: Silent Transmission and the Kung-an (K\u014dan) Tradition |title=The K\u014dan: Texts and Contexts in Zen Buddhism |pages=75\u2013109 |editor1-last=Heine |editor1-first=S. |editor2-last=Wright |editor2-first=D.S. |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |isbn=978-0-19-802780-5}}\n* {{Citation |first=A. |last=Welter |editor1-last=Buswell|editor1-first=Robert E.|title=Lineage |encyclopedia=Encyclopedia of Buddhism|date=2004|publisher=Macmillan Reference USA, [[Thomson Gale]]|volume=2 |pages=462\u2013463 <!-- |isbn=0-02-865720-9-->|isbn=978-0-02-865718-9}}\n* {{Citation |last1=Wilson |first1=L. |editor-last1=Holt |editor-first1=J. |editor-last2=Kinnard |editor-first2=J.N. |editor-last3=Walters |editor-first3=J.S. |year=2003 |chapter=Beggars Can Be Choosers: Mah\u0101kassapa as a Selective Eater of Offerings |title=Constituting Communities, Therav\u0101da Buddhism and the Religious Cultures of South and Southeast Asia |pages=57\u201370 |isbn=978-0-7914-8705-1}}\n* {{Citation |last1=Witanachchi |first1=C.|editor1-last=Malalasekera |editor1-first=G. P. |editor2-last=Weeraratne |editor2-first=W. G. |editor1-link=G. P. Malalasekera |title=\u0100nanda |encyclopedia=Encyclopaedia of Buddhism |date=1965 |publisher=[[Government of Sri Lanka]] |url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/231090852/Enceylopaedia-of-Buddhism-Vol-i |volume=1 |oclc=2863845613}}\n* {{Citation |last1=Zurcher |first1=Erik |editor1-last=Williams |editor1-first=Paul |title=Buddhism: Critical Concepts in Religious Studies, 8: Buddhism in China, East Asia, and Japan |date=2005 |publisher=[[Routledge]] |chapter=Buddhist Influence on Early Taoism |isbn=0-415-33234-6 |page=378}}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://www.accesstoinsight.org/lib/authors/hecker/wheel345.html Mah\u0101 Kassapa, Father of the Sangha], by Hellmuth Hecker, biography based on the [[Pali Canon|P\u0101li Canon]], revised and enlarged translation from Wissen und Wandel volume XXI, number 6, 1975, (German) by [[Nyanaponika]] Thera, The Wheel Publication No. 345, {{ISBN|955-24-0026-0}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20190713140808/https://www.accesstoinsight.org/lib/authors/hecker/wheel345.html archived here.]\n* [https://www.learnreligions.com/disciple-mahakasyapa-father-of-sangha-449645 ''Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa''], hosted by Learning Religion, [https://web.archive.org/web/20200217191247/https://www.learnreligions.com/disciple-mahakasyapa-father-of-sangha-449645 archived here.]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-rel|bu}}\n{{succession box|title=[[Lineage (Buddhism)|Lineage of Buddhist patriarchs]]<br /><small>(According to the [[Zen]] schools of China and Japan)</small>|before=[[Gautama Buddha|\u015a\u0101kyamuni]]<br /><small>Beginning of the lineage</small>|after=[[Ananda]]|years=}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Buddhism topics}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mahakasyapa}}\n[[Category:Foremost disciples of Gautama Buddha]]\n[[Category:Arhats]]\n[[Category:Indian Buddhist monks]]\n[[Category:Buddhist patriarchs]]\n[[Category:5th-century Buddhist monks]]\n", "name_user": "Farang Rak Tham", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNarratives:reordering references", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mah%C4%81k%C4%81%C5%9Byapa"}
{"title_page": "Widzew \u0141\u00f3d\u017a", "text_new": "{{Infobox football club\n| clubname = RTS Widzew \u0141\u00f3d\u017a\n| image = Widzew Lodz.svg\n| image_size = 200px\n| fullname = RTS Widzew \u0141\u00f3d\u017a\n| founded = 1910 as '' TMRF Widzew'' <br> 1922 reformed as ''RTS Widzew'' <br> 2015 reformed as ''RTS Widzew''\n| dissolved = \n| ground = [[Stadion Widzewa \u0141\u00f3d\u017a im. Ludwika Sobolewskiego]]<br/>[[\u0141\u00f3d\u017a]], [[Poland]]\n| capacity = 18,008\n| chairman = {{flagicon|Poland}} Martyna Paj\u0105czek\n| manager = {{flagicon|Poland}} [[Marcin Kaczmarek (footballer, born 1974)|Marcin Kaczmarek]]\n| league = [[II liga (Poland)|II liga]] (3rd level)\n| season = 2018\u201319\n| position = [[II liga (Poland)|II liga]], 5th\n| pattern_la1 = \n| pattern_b1 = _whitearc\n| pattern_ra1 = \n| leftarm1 = ff0000\n| body1 = ff0000\n| rightarm1 = ff0000\n| shorts1 = ff0000\n| socks1 = ff0000\n| pattern_la2 = \n| pattern_b2 = _blackarc\n| pattern_ra2 = \n| leftarm2 = FFFFFF\n| body2 = FFFFFF\n| rightarm2 = FFFFFF\n| shorts2 = FFFFFF\n| socks2 = FFFFFF|\n| pattern_la3 = \n| pattern_b3 = _blackarc\n| pattern_ra3 = \n| leftarm3 = f8f238\n| body3 = f8f238\n| rightarm3 = f8f238\n| shorts3 = 000000\n| socks3 = f8f238|\n}}\n'''RTS Widzew \u0141\u00f3d\u017a''' ({{IPA-pol|\u02c8\u025br \u02c8t\u025b \u02c8\u025bs \u02c8v\u02b2idz\u025bf \u02c8wut\u0361\u0255}}) is a Polish [[football (soccer)|football]] club based in [[\u0141\u00f3d\u017a]]. The club was founded in 1910. Its official colours are red and white, hence their nicknames ''Czerwona Armia'' (Red Army) and ''Czerwono-bia\u0142o-czerwoni'' (Red-white-reds).\n\n==History==\n{{expand section|date=June 2016}}\nThe club was founded in 1910 as ''Towarzystwo Mi\u0142o\u015bnik\u00f3w Rozwoju Fizycznego Widzew (Society of Physical Development Fans Widzew)''.\n\nAfter the first world war the club was reactivated in 1922 as ''Robotnicze Towarzystwo Sportowe Widzew \u0141\u00f3d\u017a (Workers' Sports Association Widzew \u0141\u00f3d\u017a).''\n\nWidzew has won four Polish league championships (in 1981, 1982, 1996 and 1997) and the 1985 [[Polish Cup]].\n\nThey have appeared in 117 matches in European Cups, of which they won 42. Widzew knocked European giants [[Manchester United]] out of the 1980\u201381 UEFA Cup, although their biggest achievement was reaching the semi-final of the [[1982\u201383 European Cup]], eliminating then 3 times winners Liverpool along the way.\n\n===Recent history===\n[[File:1. Stadion Widzewa w budowie.jpg|thumb|250px|[[Stadion Widzewa|New ground]]]]\nIn the beginning of season 2007/2008 Widzew was bought by one of the wealthiest men in Poland \u2013 [[Sylwester Cacek]].<ref>[http://www.widzewiak.pl/dorobek/historia Historia Widzewa]</ref>\n\nIn January 2008, while playing in the [[I liga (Poland)|Second League]], the [[Polish Football Association]] ruled that Widzew \u0141\u00f3d\u017a should be relegated due to their involvement in a corruption scandal. However, Widzew became champions that year and were allowed to stay in the second division, which was renamed First League (I liga) before the start of the 2008\u201309 season. Despite the deduction of six points as a penalty, Widzew managed to become champions once again, and were finally promoted to the [[Ekstraklasa]]. In total, Widzew played 35 seasons at the highest level before being relegated in the [[2013\u201314 Ekstraklasa|2013\u201314 season]].\n\nDue to financial problems, Widzew finished last at the end of the [[2014\u201315 I Liga (Poland)|2014\u201315 I Liga season]]. Subsequently, the club ruled by Sylwester Cacek went bankrupt.\n\nIn consequence local businessmen led by [[Marcin Ferdzyn]] and [[Grzegorz Waranecki]] decided to take on amateur status as a new association called ''Stowarzyszenie Reaktywacja Tradycji Sportowych Widzew \u0141\u00f3d\u017a (Association of the Reactivation of the Sports Traditions of Widzew \u0141\u00f3d\u017a)'',<ref>[http://www.lodz.sport.pl/sport-lodz/1,117110,18288014,Jest_nowy_Widzew__Reaktywacja_Tradycji_Sportowych.html Jest nowy Widzew! Reaktywacja Tradycji Sportowych Widzew \u0141\u00f3d\u017a ]</ref> which continues the tradition of the old RTS Widzew \u0141\u00f3d\u017a. The new association was registered in a Polish court on 2.07.2015, and within a few weeks of summer 2015 they managed to find new coach [[Witold Obarek]] and collect a new squad, which started the 2015/2016 season in the [[IV liga (Poland)|fifth tier of Polish football]]. In first season in IV League Widzew has promoted to higher tier. In season 2016/17 Widzew achieved third place in III League, after [[Drw\u0119ca Nowe Miasto Lubawskie]] and [[\u0141KS \u0141\u00f3d\u017a]] but next season yielded promotion to II League. Now, on the halfway point of season 2018/19 Widzew is leader with 37 points in 17 matches.\n\n==Achievements==\n\n===Domestic===\n[[File:Stadion Widzewa Lodz - Polska.jpg|thumb|250px|[[Ultras]] of Widzew]]\n[[File:RTS Widzew \u0141\u00f3d\u017a - To ju\u017c historia.jpg|thumb|250px|[[Ultras]] of Widzew]]\n* '''[[Ekstraklasa|Ekstraklasa (First Division)]]''':\n** '''Winner (4)''': [[1980\u201381 Ekstraklasa|1980\u201381]], [[1981\u201382 Ekstraklasa|1981\u201382]], [[1995\u201396 Ekstraklasa|1995\u201396]], [[1996\u201397 Ekstraklasa|1996\u201397]]\n** '''2nd place (7)''': [[1976\u201377 Ekstraklasa|1976\u201377]], [[1978\u201379 Ekstraklasa|1978\u201379]], [[1979\u201380 Ekstraklasa|1979\u201380]], [[1982\u201383 Ekstraklasa|1982\u201383]], [[1983\u201384 Ekstraklasa|1983\u201384]], [[1994\u201395 Ekstraklasa|1994\u201395]], [[1998\u201399 Ekstraklasa|1998\u201399]]\n* '''[[Polish First League|Polish First League (Second Division)]]''':\n** '''Winner (3)''': 2005\u201306, [[2008\u201309 I liga|2008\u201309]], [[2009\u201310 I liga|2009\u201310]]\n* '''[[Polish Cup]]:'''\n** '''Winner (1)''': 1985\n* '''[[Polish SuperCup]]:'''\n** '''Winner (1)''': 1996\n** '''Finalist (1)''': 1997\n* '''[[Ekstraklasa Cup|Polish League Cup]]:'''\n** '''Finalist (1)''': 1977\n\n===Europe===\n* '''[[UEFA Champions League|UEFA Champions League/European Cup]]''':\n** '''Semi-Finalist (1)''': [[1982\u201383 European Cup|1982\u201383]]\n*'''[[Copa del Sol]]''':\n** '''Runner-up (1)''': 2013\n\n===Youth Team===\n* '''[[Football Junior Championships of Poland|Polish U-19 Runner Up]]''': 1995\n** '''Polish U-19 Bronze Medal''': 1936, 1937, 1997\n\n==Honours in the Polish Ekstraklasa (to 2008 Polish 1st Division)==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!\n!Season\n!Position\n!Matches\n!Points\n!Goals\n!W.-D.-L.\n|-\n|1\n|'''1948'''\n|14 (relegation to 2nd division)\n|26\n|13 pts.\n|31\u201399\n|5\u20133\u201318\n|-\n|2\n|'''1975/76'''\n|5\n|30\n|32 pts.\n|33\u201333\n|10\u201312\u20138\n|-\n|3\n|'''1976/77'''\n|2\n|30\n|38 pts.\n|46\u201331\n|14\u201310\u20136\n|-\n|4\n|'''1977/78'''\n|10\n|30\n|28 pts.\n|34\u201340\n|9\u201310\u201311\n|-\n|5\n|'''1978/79'''\n|2\n|30\n|39 pts.\n|37\u201326\n|14\u201311\u20135\n|-\n|6\n|'''1979/80'''\n|2\n|30\n|36 pts.\n|47\u201339\n|13\u201310\u20137\n|- bgcolor=\"00FF7F\"\n|7\n|'''1980/81'''\n|1\n|30\n|39 pts.\n|39\u201325\n|14\u201311\u20135\n|- bgcolor=\"00FF7F\"\n|8\n|'''1981/82'''\n|1\n|30\n|39 pts.\n|45\u201331\n|14\u201311\u20135\n|-\n|9\n|'''1982/83'''\n|2\n|30\n|38 pts.\n|50\u201330\n|13\u201312\u20135\n|-\n|10\n|'''1983/84'''\n|2\n|30\n|42 pts.\n|43\u201325\n|15\u201312\u20133\n|-\n|11\n|'''1984/85'''\n|3\n|30\n|38 pts.\n|34\u201316\n|13\u201312\u20135\n|-\n|12\n|'''1985/86'''\n|3\n|30\n|41 pts.\n|40\u201325\n|15\u201311\u20134\n|-\n|13\n|'''1986/87'''\n|6\n|30\n|36 pts.\n|34\u201329\n|14\u20137\u20139\n|-\n|14\n|'''1987/88'''\n|5\n|30\n|31 pts.\n|28\u201324\n|8\u201315\u20137\n|-\n|15\n|'''1988/89''' <small></small>\n|7\n|30\n|29 pts.\n|27\u201327\n|9\u201312\u20139\n|-\n|16\n|'''1989/90'''\n|15 (relegation to 2nd division.)\n|30\n|17 pts.\n|22\u201339\n|4\u201312\u201314\n|-\n|17\n|'''1991/92'''\n|3\n|34\n|43 pts.\n|48\u201328\n|17\u20139\u20138\n|-\n|18\n|'''1992/9